BACKGROUND: Student Run Clinics (SRCs) are a common aspect of medical education, 
present at more than half of US medical schools, and noted for providing care to 
communities that might otherwise lack access, including the uninsured and 
underinsured. To date, few studies have rigorously quantified the health and 
economic benefits of SRCs, and the present study remedies that.
METHODS AND FINDINGS: We used Monte Carlo simulations to estimate the health 
impact of common preventive health interventions applied to individuals in 
quality-adjusted life-years (QALYs). We then used those measurements to estimate 
